sentences: Karan Casey (born 1969) is an Irish folk singer, and a former member of the Irish band Solas.
At Waterford Regional Technical College she studied piano then took music at University College Dublin in 1987.
In 1993, Casey moved to New York City, to study jazz at Long Island University.
During 1994, she sang with Atlantic Bridge before joining Solas, recording five songs on their début album in 1996.
During 1994, she sang with Atlantic Bridge before joining Solas, recording five songs on their début album in 1996.
In 1997, Casey recorded a solo album, Songlines, inspired by the novel of the same name by Bruce Chatwin and produced by Séamus Egan.
In 2000, she collaborated with several other vocalists on Seal Maiden: a Celtic Musical.
In 2001, Casey finished working on her second solo album, The Winds Begin to Sing (2001) which was well received by critics and propelled her into a stable solo career.
She released Distant Shore in 2003 and toured extensively throughout the Americas and Europe.
In 2005, Casey released Chasing the Sun featuring Irish traditional and folk songs which she learned from her mother and maternal grandmother.
In 2006, Casey joined her previous band Solas to guest on their live DVD and album, Reunion: a Decade of Solas.
She joined Deirdre Scanlan (Solas vocalist 2000–2007) and Antje Duvekot, along with the male vocalists from the band.
In 2008, Casey and her husband set up Crow Valley Music to release Ships in the Forest.
In early 2010, Casey released Exiles Return, a duet album with former Solas bandmate John Doyle; it was listed among the Top 5 albums of the year by The Irish Echo newspaper.
Released in 2014, Two More Hours was Casey's sixth solo album and her first entirely self-penned work.

In 2017 Karan was Traditional Artist in Residenceat University College Cork, toured the UK with the Transatlantic Sessions, performed at Glasgow's Celtic Connections, and toured in the US both with her own band and with Lúnasa, including a performance at New York's Carnegie Hall.
In 2018 Karan helped to found FairPlé which is an organization aimed at achieving fairness and gender balance for female performers in Irish traditional and folk musics.
In 2019 she released her latest album Hieroglyphs That Tell the Tale on the Vertical Records Label.

Casey left Solas at the beginning of 1999 to pursue her solo ambitions.
Early years ==
Having learned to copy Ella Fitzgerald's scat singing, she performed in a Dublin bistro several nights per week while still a student.
In 2005, Casey released Chasing the Sun featuring Irish traditional and folk songs which she learned from her mother and maternal grandmother.
In 2006, Casey joined her previous band Solas to guest on their live DVD and album, Reunion: a Decade of Solas.
In early 2010, Casey released Exiles Return, a duet album with former Solas bandmate John Doyle; it was listed among the Top 5 albums of the year by The Irish Echo newspaper.
Released in 2014, Two More Hours was Casey's sixth solo album and her first entirely self-penned work.
A departure from the traditional music she has focused on for many years, Two More Hours draws on Casey's lifelong love of R&B, jazz and blues in creating a vibrant new mix of sounds.

Casey has also collaborated with Bela Fleck, Maura O'Connell, Tim O'Brien, Lunasa, The Boston Pops Orchestra, The Dubliners & Imelda May, A Stór Mo Chroí (featuring John Spillane, Lumiere and Muireann Nic Amhlaoibh), among others.
She has two daughters (Muireann and Áine) and currently lives in Cork.
